Name: RCR - Responsible Conduct of Research
Description:
Responsible Conduct of Research (RCR) Orientation: Master's Students
Duke University Graduate School
Wednesday, August 23, 2023
9:00 am to 12:00 pm EDT
Online via Zoom in Duke Sakai: Grad School Orientation

Responsible Conduct of Research training is a formal requirement for every master’s and PhD student enrolled in The Graduate School. The RCR training requirement reflects our expectation that every graduate student will be aware of academic standards and well-qualified to address the growing ethical challenges that arise when teaching or conducting scholarly research. 
 
This year, RCR orientation is being held entirely online via Zoom on Sakai, Duke's learning management platform. The Sakai site Grad School Orientation will include the Zoom links. Note that you'll need to log in with your Duke NetID and password. 

To receive transcript credit for this RCR event, you will need to attend the entire event (it begins at 9:00 am and ends by 12:00 pm, short break in the middle). When you log into Sakai with your Duke NetID, your participation in the Zoom sessions will be logged, and credit will be awarded based on those logs. Please don't arrive late or leave early.  
 
Your RCR orientation will consist of two Zoom sessions: starting at 9:00, you will engage with Kimberly Hewitt, Vice President for Institutional Equity and Chief Diversity Officer. During this session, you'll also have a chance to meet some of your new colleagues and engage in discussion of diversity and inclusion in a research environment. This session will earn credit for GS715 on your transcript.
 
In your second session, which begins at 10:30, you'll have a chance to work in a smaller, more discipline-specific group led by Duke faculty. You'll be discussing ethical challenges you'll face in your field. This session will earn credit for GS714 on your transcript. 
 
At this orientation, you'll also have a chance to learn more about the ongoing RCR training you'll be expected to engage in during your graduate studies. 

If you need a disability-related accommodation for the RCR orientation, please contact Dr. Hugh Crumley (crumley@duke.edu) by August 5.

Name: Reunion Weekend Celebration Breakfast
Description:
Greetings, Duke Statistical Science Students!

You are cordially invited to our very casual Reunion Weekend Celebration Breakfast, on Saturday, April 13th. It has been at least five years since the Duke Department of Statistical Science has hosted a reunions reception event.   We'll gather casually in the Lobby of Old Chemistry for bagels (with all the fixings), coffee, and other light breakfast items. We'll be there from 9 to 1045 am.  Stop by and say hello, grab a bite, or stay and chat for a while. We will spill over to the porch and outside if it gets crowded. 


This will be a great chance to casually meet some department alumni. Elizabeth Ratliff, BS 2019, who is organizing the event on behalf of the undergraduate alumni, is a data scientist at Disney in New York and an actor.  When COVID-19 hit, she combined her interests and developed Statisflix.  


This reunion weekend is focusing on the class years ending in 4 and 9, including the undergraduate reunion classes of 2009, 2015, and 2019. If you would like to join us to meet some of them,  please RSVP by April 10th at https://duke.is/StatSciBreakfast.    


Hope to see you there!


Joan 




Joan Combs Durso, Ph.D.

Description:
Applied Statistics Seminar by Prof. Minh-Ngoc Tran, University of Sydney

Title: Statistics in the data-centric era

Invited Speaker: Professor Minh-Ngoc Tran, Business School, University of Sydney, Australia.

Time: 2PM, Wednesday July 19, 2023.

Location: Room A2. 511, International University, VNU-HCM.

Abstract: Statistics has demonstrated it is escalating significance in the data-centric era, manifesting itself as both a specialized academic discipline and an interdisciplinary field. In this presentation, I aim to provide a birds-eye overview of Bayesian statistics and shed light on its recent advancements. I will then delve into two specific statistical applications that have occupied my attention over the past few years: financial econometrics and empirical psychology. Throughout the discussion, I will recount my personal experiences collaborating with psychologists and financial econometricians as a statistician, emphasizing the invaluable insights gained from these interactions.
